ExtraaLearn Project¶

Context¶

The EdTech industry has been surging in the past decade immensely, and according to a forecast, the Online Education market would be worth $286.62bn by 2023 with a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 10.26% from 2018 to 2023. The modern era of online education has enforced a lot in its growth and expansion beyond any limit. Due to having many dominant features like ease of information sharing, personalized learning experience, transparency of assessment, etc, it is now preferable to traditional education.

In the present scenario due to the Covid-19, the online education sector has witnessed rapid growth and is attracting a lot of new customers. Due to this rapid growth, many new companies have emerged in this industry. With the availability and ease of use of digital marketing resources, companies can reach out to a wider audience with their offerings. The customers who show interest in these offerings are termed as leads. There are various sources of obtaining leads for Edtech companies, like

  • The customer interacts with the marketing front on social media or other online platforms.
  • The customer browses the website/app and downloads the brochure
  • The customer connects through emails for more information.

The company then nurtures these leads and tries to convert them to paid customers. For this, the representative from the organization connects with the lead on call or through email to share further details.

Objective¶

ExtraaLearn is an initial stage startup that offers programs on cutting-edge technologies to students and professionals to help them upskill/reskill. With a large number of leads being generated on a regular basis, one of the issues faced by ExtraaLearn is to identify which of the leads are more likely to convert so that they can allocate resources accordingly. You, as a data scientist at ExtraaLearn, have been provided the leads data to:

  • Analyze and build an ML model to help identify which leads are more likely to convert to paid customers,
  • Find the factors driving the lead conversion process
  • Create a profile of the leads which are likely to convert

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of leads and their interaction details with ExtraaLearn. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary

  • ID: ID of the lead
  • age: Age of the lead
  • current_occupation: Current occupation of the lead. Values include 'Professional','Unemployed',and 'Student'
  • first_interaction: How did the lead first interacted with ExtraaLearn. Values include 'Website', 'Mobile App'
  • profile_completed: What percentage of profile has been filled by the lead on the website/mobile app. Values include Low - (0-50%), Medium - (50-75%), High (75-100%)
  • website_visits: How many times has a lead visited the website
  • time_spent_on_website: Total time spent on the website
  • page_views_per_visit: Average number of pages on the website viewed during the visits.

  • last_activity: Last interaction between the lead and ExtraaLearn.

    • Email Activity: Seeking for details about program through email, Representative shared information with lead like brochure of program , etc
    • Phone Activity: Had a Phone Conversation with representative, Had conversation over SMS with representative, etc
    • Website Activity: Interacted on live chat with representative, Updated profile on website, etc

  • print_media_type1: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn in the Newspaper.

  • print_media_type2: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn in the Magazine.
  • digital_media: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn on the digital platforms.
  • educational_channels: Flag indicating whether the lead had heard about ExtraaLearn in the education channels like online forums, discussion threads, educational websites, etc.
  • referral: Flag indicating whether the lead had heard about ExtraaLearn through reference.
  • status: Flag indicating whether the lead was converted to a paid customer or not.

From the initial summary statistics we can infer the following points for each continuous variable:

age - There is a slight left skew in the data as the mean is 46.2 whereas the median is 51. This is likely an indication that the audience is generally older, which aligns with our target audience of experienced professionals looking to upskill / reskill. This indication can also be seen as positive since younger people generally have less buying power.

website_visits - website visits seems to have a bit more of a symmetrical / normal distribution. The max of 30, which is significantly above the mean 3.5 with a standard deviation of 2.8 suggests the likelihood of outlier(s) that can be addressed. This may be related to a customer that is indecisive about the product, however, we can see that this is not the typical behavior of people engaging with the website.

time_spent_on_website - There appears to be a right skew in the data as the mean is 724.01, whereas the median is 376. There may also be a presence of outliers, however, the maximum is not greater than 1.5 IQR as there is a pretty large standard deviation. Depending on the EDA we will understand whether any manipulation should be completed.

page_views_per_visit - There appears to be minimal right skew on this variable, however, due to the maximum 18.434 where the mean is 3.03 and the standard deviation is 1.97 we expect there to be outliers in this variable.

Based on the initial analysis of the distribution of our categorical variables we can see that:

current_occupation - 57% of engagement is from Professionals, which means they likely have more spending power compared to the Unemployed and Student population. The Student population is only 12%, which aligns with our initial observation that the age distribution is generally higher. A 31% distribution of Unemployed searchers is also significant as they will likely have more time to dedicate to the course and may be willing to make the purchase.

first_interaction - The Website and Mobile App do not have significantly different distributions in the sample, however, it is clear that the website drives more traffic than the Mobile App. This may be due to the element of having to download a Mobile App in order to use it as opposed to using the website on the browser - there is less friction related to interacting with the Website.

profile_completed - 98% of our dataset has at least Medium complete profile with only 2% of observations in Low complete status. Higher completion may be preferrable as it demonstrates greater interest and investment by taking the time to complete the profile.

last_activity - 49% of the data has a last activity through the Email channel, which allows for more opportunities to provide information in the form of attachments and follow-up communications.

Marketing Channels

  • print_media_type1 - 11% of our sample saw the ad in the newspaper.
  • print_media_type2 - 5% of our sample saw the ad in Magazines.
  • digital_media- 11% of our sample saw the ad through digital channels.
  • educational_channels - 15% of our sample saw the ad through educational channels.
    • It appears that Newspapers and Digital channels had similar rates of impressions and lead generation
    • Magazines had less success in generating leads
    • Newspapers may be preforming well due to the age distribution of leads
    • There may be an opportunity to increase penetration of digital media as there should be less friction surrounding converting a digital ad into a lead
    • Educational channels had the best penetration, which may be expected as the target audience would likely be interacting with these channels

referral - only 2% of leads came from referrals. There is a positive that marketing initiatives are successfully reaching new users, however, word of mouth is known to be a powerful driver for decision-making so understanding the satisfaction of current users and how to improve the product could be a good strategy for increasing referrals and lead conversions.

status - about 30% of leads were converted, which represents an opportunity for improvement. This will be the dependent variable that we will use in our models, which we can see is imbalanced.

# Define hist_box() function to view both a histogram and boxplot in the same visual

def hist_box(df, col):
  f, (ax_box, ax_hist) = plt.subplots(2, sharex=True, gridspec_kw={'height_ratios':(0.15,.850)}, figsize=(12,6))
  # Add a graph in each part
  sns.boxplot(data = df, x=col, ax = ax_box, showmeans=True, color = 'mintcream')
  sns.histplot(data = df, x=col, kde=True, ax=ax_hist)
  ax_hist.axvline(df[col].mean(), color = 'green', linestyle = '--')
  ax_hist.axvline(df[col].median(), color = 'black', linestyle = "-")

  plt.show()

# Using a heatmap to determine the correlation between continuous variables

cols_list = df.select_dtypes(include=np.number).columns.tolist()

plt.show()
  • The continuous variables appear to have very little correlation between one another, which increases our confidence in the independence of these variables and eligibility to be used in our analysis
  • There is a very slight negative correlation between age and website visits, which suggests that as age increases, the number of website visits decrease
    • Younger people may need to refer to the website more often to ensure that the courses are a good investment
  • There is a very slight positive correlation between age and time spent on the website, which suggests that as age increases, the amount of time spent on the site increases
    • Older people may read the information more thoroughly when they engage with the website

  • There is a very slight negative correlation between age and average page views per visit, which suggests that as age increases, the average number of pages viewed decreases

    • Young people may have a higher tendency to skim, which could help in determining the content strategy on the website

  • As website visits increase, time spent increases

    • Leads who frequent the site more often are more likely to dedicate a higher time investment to the decision

  • as time spent on website increases, page views increase

    • more time on the website allows leads to browse through more pages of the site

# Define the stacked barplot function

def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target, figsize=(5, 3)):
    # Create a crosstab with percentages
    crosstab = (pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize='index') * 100)

    # Create the stacked barplot
    ax = crosstab.plot(kind='bar', figsize=figsize, stacked=True)

    # Add percentage labels on top of the bars
    for container in ax.containers:
        ax.bar_label(container, fmt='%.2f%%', label_type='edge', fontsize = 7)

    plt.legend(loc='lower right')
    plt.ylabel(target)
    plt.show()

Questions¶

  1. Leads will have different expectations from the outcome of the course and the current occupation may play a key role in getting them to participate in the program. Find out how current occupation affects lead status.

Current occupation affects lead status as Professionals have the highest conversion rate in this feature. As mentioned in our observations, this could be due to greater disposable income. Professionals that are looking at working on a course at the same time as their full time job may be driven by ambition to upskill and increase their position in their current company, which may make these leads more likely to convert as they have a specific goal. The details of the program will also be important as it may be designed to be completed at the same time as a full-time job and marketed more directly towards this segment.
Unemployed professionals have the second highest conversion rate, which may be similar to Professionals in that they have an ambition to secure a job in the related field. There might be lower conversion because these individuals may be looking more for full-time learning opportunities or want to have a program that has a stronger emphasis on job-placement. As most of the observations in the sample are of higher age-groups, most leads may also fall in these two segments as opposed to the student segment.

  1. The company's first impression on the customer must have an impact. Do the first channels of interaction have an impact on the lead status?

Yes, first impression on the website have a significantly higher conversion rate than first impressions on the Mobile App. This is interesting considering that in order to engage with an app there must be a download, which introduces friction. The website may be very well designed for lead conversion and have the right kind of marketing and program information that leads need in order to change status. The Mobile App is a digital asset that needs support in this area as 45% of first impressions are starting in that channel. This represents an opportunity to improve conversion.

  1. The company uses multiple modes to interact with prospects. Which way of interaction works best?

From the data provided it appears that the Website interaction works best. It is important to note that we are talking about the last activity, which means that email and phone activity may have been a mode used early in the interaction and the last interaction was website interaction. Looking specifically at website interaction, the live chat feature may be well designed to resolve lead questions and drive greater conversion and the communication strategy of emails and phone calls can be further investigated to better engage with leads.

  1. The company gets leads from various channels such as print media, digital media, referrals, etc. Which of these channels have the highest lead conversion rate?

As mentioned in the Bi-variate analysis, referrals had the highest conversion rate at about 68%. This is significant because it is the channel that has the lowest number observations representing only 2% of the sample. It may be the case that there is a Bias in that people do not always indicate when they were referred, however, it is a channel that could present a large opportunity to increase sales. Of the other modes, there is very little data showing that the type of media affects whether a conversion happens or not as conversion rates are similar for both yes and no observations. Magazine ads, which only drive 5% impressions was the second best performing channel.

  1. People browsing the website or mobile application are generally required to create a profile by sharing their personal data before they can access additional information.Does having more details about a prospect increase the chances of conversion?

Having more details does improve the prospect of conversion, as high completion has a 42% conversion rate in our sample. This may be that leads who are willing to include personal information are more serious about converting. However, the low conversion rates on Medium and Low completion means that the communication strategy may be lacking important information for these leads that could lead to more conversions

# Define hist_box() function to view both a histogram and boxplot in the same visual

def hist_box(df, col):
  f, (ax_box, ax_hist) = plt.subplots(2, sharex=True, gridspec_kw={'height_ratios':(0.15,.850)}, figsize=(12,6))
  # Add a graph in each part
  sns.boxplot(data = df, x=col, ax = ax_box, showmeans=True, color = 'mintcream')
  sns.histplot(data = df, x=col, kde=True, ax=ax_hist)
  ax_hist.axvline(df[col].mean(), color = 'green', linestyle = '--')
  ax_hist.axvline(df[col].median(), color = 'black', linestyle = "-")

  plt.show()

Building a Decision Tree model¶

Model Evaluation Criteria¶

There are two ways the model can be wrong:

  1. The model can predict that the lead will convert, but the lead will not convert (False Positive)
    • The risk is dedicating company resources to a potential customer that will not be converted
  2. The model can predict that the lead will not covert, but the lead would convert (False Negative)
    • The risk is missing out on a potential paying customer

In this case, the company is looking to maximize Recall, since missing out on a potential customer is greater than the risk of dedicating resources for lead conversion Even if the targeted customer is not converted, the resources for conversion might work on additional customers.

In [336]:
# Creating a metric function to measure and maximize the possibility of recall

def metrics_score(actual,predicted):
  print(classification_report(actual, predicted))

  cm = confusion_matrix(actual, predicted)
  plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))

  sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='.2f')
  plt.ylabel('Actual')
  plt.xlabel('Predicted')
  plt.show()

Do we need to prune the tree?¶

Yes, at first glance it seems that we will need to prune the tree due to overfitting. Further analysis will explain whether or not the pruned tree performs better than the original model.

Do we need to prune the tree?¶

Yes, the model appears to be over-fitting to the training data and could benefit from pruning to increase recall.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

For the purposes of this analysis, I will assume that the variables and data collection process was standardized for all observations, especially for those that depend on a time duration in order to be measured. I am interested in understanding how leads are interacting with the company's digital assets to make recommendations on how to improve. Absent this assumption, I would have dropped more variables that are not immediately available the moment a lead is generated such as: website_visits , time_spent_on_website,page_views_per_visit

Based on the outputs of both the Random Forest and Decision Tree Models, the 4 most important features determining conversion in the sample are: First Interaction, Total Time Spent on the Website, Profile Completion, and Age, with First interaction (DT) and Time Spent (RF) being the two most important depending on the model. The Random Forest Model performed best with 84% recall vs. the Decision Tree Model with a recall of 82%. Both of these pruned models greatly reduce the number of False Negatives, allowing ExtraaLearn to maximize the number of paying customers they can convert with the available resources.

Final Recommendations

  1. Improve Mobile App Experience - About 45% of leads have their first experience on the Mobile App, whereas 55% of leads have their first impression on the website. Despite a pretty similar distribution across channels, Mobile App Conversion was 10.53%, whereas Website Conversion was 45.59%. There appears to be a significant gap in the information that is presented on the Mobile App vs. the information that is presented on the Website that allows for Website conversion to have such a significantly higher rate. Tailoring content strategy to Mobile App users and understanding their customer journey will allow for a material improvement in conversions, especially considering this feature was the number one most important in the Decision Tree model for prediction.

  2. Build a Community on Digital Platforms - Total time spent on the website was the most important feature to predict conversions in the Random Forest Model. Increasing the opportunities for leads to engage with the ExtraaLearn brand, and providing useful information to make leads want to spend more time on the website and other digital assets is expected to have a significant effect in increasing conversions. As many leads are Professionals and value continuous learning / upskilling, capitalizing on networking through discussion forums and providing industry research / knowledge in blog posts will increase the value of professional development provided by the ExtraaLearn brand and will help grow a vibrant community on the digital platforms. Additionally, it could lead to effects such as increasing referrals, which is a feature that plays an important role in the Decision Tree model, and from EDA we know could be greatly improved as there are few observations but very high conversion rates.

  3. Reduce Friction in Profile Completion - Implementing integrations with existing platforms that collect customer data such as Meta, Google, and LinkedIn can be an important strategy for increasing conversions. Just this year we saw how the integration with Instagram of the sister app Threads broke records of user sign ups due to the reduced friction in creating a profile. In our models, even just a Medium complete profile makes a material difference in conversions. Allowing customers to quickly create a profile and access the important information within the required platform can help to increase conversion.

  4. Age - In our models, age was also consistently one of the determining factors in conversion. Implementing one of the previous strategies of understanding the customer journey will allow ExtraaLearn to build personas around their potential leads and implement campaigns that have higher conversion rates. From EDA, we saw that there were generational patterns in the multimodal nature of the distribution, which can be used to design the right products and engagement strategies in the future.
